What CC-BY-4.0 covers — and what it does not
--------------------------------------------

CC-BY-4.0 attaches to the *compilation*: the selection of CPT codes, our
original plain-language service labels, the geographic arrangement by CMS
locality, the schema, and the documented methodology that assembles these
figures. It is the creative and editorial work of building the dataset that
is licensed here.

CC-BY-4.0 does NOT — and cannot — place new restrictions on the underlying
public-domain facts. The raw CMS RVU and GPCI numeric values, the conversion
factor, and the Medicare allowed amounts derived directly from them are facts
drawn from U.S. Government works (see below) and remain in the public domain.
Anyone may use those underlying numbers freely from their original public
sources; the CC-BY-4.0 terms apply to this particular compiled, labeled, and
arranged dataset.


Underlying CMS data — U.S. Government works, public domain
----------------------------------------------------------

The numeric inputs are derived from the Centers for Medicare & Medicaid
Services (CMS) Physician Fee Schedule release:

    PPRRVU2026_Jan_nonQPP.csv   (work / PE / MP RVUs, status, conversion factor)
    GPCI2026.csv                (geographic practice cost indices per locality)

Works prepared by U.S. Government employees as part of their official duties
are not subject to copyright in the United States (17 U.S.C. § 105) and are in
the public domain. These source files are re-fetchable via `fetch_cms_data.sh`
and are intentionally NOT committed to this repository (see `.gitignore`).


